ur Conversions" alt="WordPress SEO Mistakes that are Killing Your Conversions" style="width: 100%!important;"></a></p><p style="padding: 0 26px !important; margin: 0 !important;">If you’re pouring time and money into SEO without tracking conversions, then you’re making a big mistake. Remember that web traffic is meaningless if you’re not converting anyone into leads or paying customers. It’s like setting up shop on a busy street where hundreds of people come and go to your shop, yet none of [&#8230;]<p style="margin: 0!important;padding: 26px 0 0!important;"><a href="https://oceanwp.org/wordpress-seo-mistakes-killing-conversions/" target="_blank" style="display: inline-block; padding: 10px 30px; color: #ffffff; background-color: #13aff0; border-radius: 30px; font-size: 13px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4; text-transform: uppercase; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; letter-spacing: 1px;">Read More</a></p></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Marc Sullivan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11776:"<p style="display: block; padding: 0 0 24px; margin: 0 !important;"><a href="https://oceanwp.org/wordpress-seo-mistakes-killing-conversions/" target="_blank"><img src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/1200-x-600.jpg" width="1200" height="600" title="WordPress SEO Mistakes that are Killing Your Conversions" alt="WordPress SEO Mistakes that are Killing Your Conversions" style="width: 100%!important;"></a></p><p style="padding: 0 26px !important; margin: 0 !important;"><p>If you’re pouring time and money into SEO without tracking conversions, then you’re making a big mistake.</p>\n<p>Remember that web traffic is meaningless if you’re not converting anyone into leads or paying customers. It’s like setting up shop on a busy street where hundreds of people come and go to your shop, yet none of bought anything from you.</p>\n<p>It sounds pretty sad, doesn’t it?</p>\n<p>The sad part is, a good number of website owners — particularly DIY WordPress users — are unaware of the link between <a href="https://oceanwp.org/complete-seo-audit-checklist/">SEO</a> and conversions. They think SEO is exclusively about bringing people in.</p>\n<p>In this post, we’ll show how dangerous that line of reasoning is.</p>\n<p>We’ll expose some of the SEO mistakes that not only hold your rankings back but also <i>kill</i> your conversions.</p>\n<p>Let’s jump into it.</p>\n<h2>1. Not Managing Your Search Visibility</h2>\n<p>An average WordPress blogger probably doesn’t know that there is an option to discourage search engine crawlers from indexing your website.</p>\n<p>You may be thinking, “<i>isn’t it the goal of SEO to be indexed and rank in search engine results pages?</i>”</p>\n<p>That’s right — unless your website is still under construction with placeholder text and images all over the place. </p>\n<p>Keep in mind that a search engine crawler’s job is to evaluate the <i>relevance</i> and <i>quality</i> of every content they pass through.</p>\n<p><i>You don’t want them to discover your website with dozens of copies of “Lorem Ipsum.”</i></p>\n<p>So, as you develop your content, head to the “Settings” tab and click “Reading.” From there, check “Discourage search engines from indexing this site” and click “Save Changes.”</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-122910 size-full" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-1.png" alt="" width="625" height="319" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-1.png 625w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-1-300x153.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></p>\n<p>Whatever you do, <b>don’t forget to disable this option once you have sufficient quality content on your website</b><i>. </i>Create a “pre-launch checklist” that includes proofreading everything, removing placeholder images, and disabling this option. </p>\n<h2>2. Ignoring Website Speed</h2>\n<p>Let’s say you finally attained a decent ranking in one of your keywords.</p>\n<p><i>You’re stoked.</i></p>\n<p>But after a couple of days, you realize that more people are bouncing off your website than converting.</p>\n<p>The first suspect is your website’s <i>loading speed, </i>which can quickly put off your potential leads — prompting them to look elsewhere for what they need.</p>\n<p>According to Kissmetrics, around <a href="https://blog.kissmetrics.com/loading-time/">40% of users</a> don’t hesitate to leave websites that take over 3 seconds to load.</p>\n<p>That’s nearly <i>half </i>of your prospects gone before you even get the chance to convert them.</p>\n<p>On top of the higher bounce rate, your website’s loading speed is also one of the known on-page SEO factors.</p>\n<p>Fortunately, <a href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-performance-speed/">boosting your WP speed performance</a> isn’t necessarily difficult.</p>\n<p>With plugins like <a href="https://wp-rocket.me/">WP Rocket</a> and <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/imagify/">Imagify Image Optimizer</a>, you can easily integrate features that can optimize your website’s loading speed. This includes lossless image compression, database caching, and code minification.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-122913 size-full" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-2.png" alt="" width="667" height="269" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-2.png 667w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-2-300x121.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /></p>\n<p>You can also use <a href="https://developers.google.com/speed/pagespeed/insights/">Google PageSpeed Insights</a> for a more thorough assessment of your website’s performance. In addition to detecting the issues that demand your immediate attention, it’ll also provide you with recommendations on how to fix them.</p>\n<p><img class="wp-image-122914 size-full alignnone" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-3.png" alt="" width="641" height="287" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-3.png 641w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-3-300x134.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 641px) 100vw, 641px" /></p>\n<h2>3. Targeting Broad Keywords</h2>\n<p>If you want your SEO to generate profitable results, you need to make sure you’re <i>targeting the right keywords. </i></p>\n<p>You may have heard of this advice several times before, but it bears repeating:</p>\n<p><b>Don’t target broad keywords regardless of their traffic potential</b><i>. </i></p>\n<p>Doing so will pit you against better-funded competitors — usually with a dedicated SEO team that works round the clock. </p>\n<p>Instead, you should look for <i>long-tail keywords </i>that are not only less competitive, but also target a narrower, more driven audience. </p>\n<p>A keyword research tool like <a href="https://neilpatel.com/ubersuggest/">Ubersuggest</a> can help with this by expanding a seed keyword into <i>hundreds </i>of long-tail keyword suggestions within seconds. Simply enter any relevant term or phrase into the main field and click “Look Up.”</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-122915 size-full" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-4.png" alt="" width="657" height="325" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-4.png 657w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-4-300x148.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 657px) 100vw, 657px" /></p>\n<p>Apart from keyword suggestions, Ubersuggest also provides essential metrics that help gauge their feasibility. </p>\n<p>When researching keywords with Ubersuggest, a rule of thumb is to avoid keywords with a competition rating of 1.0. In fact, if you’ve never done SEO before, you should shoot for keywords with a competition rating of 0.4 or less.</p>\n<p>You should also use the “Filter Results” tool to find keywords with commercial or question-based terms, like “how to,” “buy,” or “hire.” These are usually found in keywords that are used by people who are just about ready to take action. </p>\n<h2>4. Not Using Keywords Properly</h2>\n<p>After you identify your target keywords, you don’t just mention it <i>once </i>in an article and call it a day. </p>\n<p>Take note that search keywords pertain to a user’s expectations. </p>\n<p>If you want to engage and compel them to convert, your content must be built around your keyword strategy.</p>\n<p><b>Keywords must be the primary focus of your content, not just something you add after the fact. </b></p>\n<p>How to make sure you accomplish this? Well, if you can insert your target keyword naturally in the right places, then you’ll know you’re on the right track. </p>\n<p>A tool like <a href="https://yoast.com/wordpress/plugins/seo/">Yoast SEO</a> can help guide you on how to weave your target keyword into your content. It works by analyzing your post’s keyword optimization in real-time, providing clear, easy-to-follow guidelines.</p>\n<p><img class="wp-image-122916 size-full aligncenter" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-5.png" alt="" width="634" height="372" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-5.png 634w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-5-300x176.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 634px) 100vw, 634px" /></p>\n<p>Yoast SEO also allows you to edit your post’s meta description, URL slug, and page title — all in the same place. </p>\n<p>You guessed it — these are also great areas to put your target keywords.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-122917 size-full" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-6.png" alt="SEO, Conversion, WordPress, CRO" width="618" height="424" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-6.png 618w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-6-300x206.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 618px) 100vw, 618px" /></p>\n<p>Yoast SEO also allows you to edit your post’s meta description, URL slug, and page title — all in the same place. </p>\n<p>You guessed it — these are also great areas to put your target keywords. </p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-122918 size-full" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-7.png" alt="SEO, Conversions, WordPress, CRO" width="632" height="519" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-7.png 632w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-7-300x246.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 632px) 100vw, 632px" /></p>\n<h2>5. You Use a Non-SEO-Friendly Permalink Structure</h2>\n<p>Finally, don’t forget that search engines like Google are all about user experience. </p>\n<p>That’s why you shouldn’t stop until every single detail of your WordPress website is optimized for user experience, including your website’s <i>permalink structure. </i></p>\n<p>The key here is to use something that’s readable, enticing, and memorable to your users. And with WordPress, the most SEO-friendly permalink structures would be the “Post Name” format and a custom structure that includes the category.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-122919 size-full" src="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-8.png" alt="SEO, Conversions, WordPress, CRO" width="627" height="234" style="width: auto; margin: 40px auto;" srcset="https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-8.png 627w, https://oceanwp.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/image-8-300x112.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 627px) 100vw, 627px" /></p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>If you want your WordPress website to generate truckloads of money, then you need to do SEO and CRO hand in hand.</p>\n<p>Of course, neither aspect is meant to be easy. But once you understand and correct what you’ve been doing wrong, you should be well on your way to unlocking your website’s maximum profit potential. </p>\n<p>What were the particular WordPress SEO mistakes have you committed in the past? Think we missed something that definitely deserves a mention?</p>\n<p>Feel free to leave a comment below!</p>\n<p style="margin: 0!important;padding: 26px 0 0!important;"><a href="https://oceanwp.org/wordpress-seo-mistakes-killing-conversions/" target="_blank" style="display: inline-block; padding: 10px 30px; color: #ffffff; background-color: #13aff0; border-radius: 30px; font-size: 13px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4; text-transform: uppercase; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; letter-spacing: 1px;">Read More</a></p></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:68:"https://oceanwp.org/wordpress-seo-mistakes-killing-conversions/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"4";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:51:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:85:"How to Convert Visitors into Email Subscribers and Keep Them Engaged with Newsletters";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0